Mechanism of recovery of AKI

Assessment of renal function - eGFR and creatinine

In practice creatinine is used because it is an endogenous substance.
Creatinine is a small molecule, eliminated only by filtration and secretion.
The half life of creatinine is 3.8 hours. (prolonged in kidney injury)

  • Therefore, using creatinine as the molecule slightly overestimates the GFR.
  • Accurately measuring creatinine clearance would require measuring urine creatinine.
  • So for convenience, we measure the serum creatinine and approximate the GFR based on that.
    The basis of all all these formulas is :
    Rate of elimination = rate of production = Serum Cr. x Clearance.
    Rate of production is estimated by age, sex etc.
    Therefore, clearance can be calculated. (assuming the contribution from tubular filtration is minimal)
    [!INFO] Non linear S.Cr. relationship
    The relationship between S.cr and GFR is not linear.

[!INFO] How fast does creatinine rise in AKI?
Creatinin rises within hours. The rate of rise if fast enough that using only creatinin levels to monitor AKI causes delays in diagnosis of AKI. Source

link: [[Acute Kidney Injury - SHTOP]]

  • ACEi and ARBs decrease the efferent arteriolar vasoconstriction caused by angiotensin II.
  • This action is renoprotective in early DM and CKD with proteinuria because it reduces hyperfiltration Source
  • However, in low perfusion states, loss of RAAS mediated efferent arteriolar vasoconstriction prevents the required compensatory efferent vasoconstriction which normally maintains GFR in low perfusion states. Source

"ACEi are not nephrotoxic per se but they are known to cause AKI in patients with dehytration .." Source

  • Therefore, ACEi and ARBs can contribute to AKI.
  • Triple therapy of NSAID + diuretic (induces low volume state) + ACEi / ARB is particularly dangerous.

[!TIP] Mnemonic: For duration of action
RSILP - 4, 8, 16, 22, 24
